= The Coservatorio Congress

# reference: Evans, Ellen L. “Adam Stegerwald and the Role of the Christian Trade Unions in the Weimar Republic.” The Catholic Historical Review 59, no. 4 (1974): 602–26.

On  June  11th the delegates of the CNT convened to resolve the big questions dividing the union. The congress is split in two sides, with some exceptions.
On one hand, there are the delegates around Angel Pestana (reformists) and Joan Peiro (unionists), who are, more or less, supportive of the Republic and more friendly to the leftist parties in the upcoming Constituent Cortes. The leading faces among these delegates are, like Sr. Peiro, members of the National Committee. Sr. Pestana himself is the Chairman of the Committee. The editorial committee of the union's main newspaper in Barcelon, Solidaridad Obrera, is also full of their sympathisers
On the other hand are the more militant faistas and especially the people arounf the Nosotros group (Buenaventura Durruti, Francisco Ascaso and Juan Garcia Oliver), as well of the more dogmatic anarchists, like Sr. Abad de Santillan. Being inspired by the struggles of their exile revolutionaries, these delegates are more radical in their demands and their actions. They oppose any tollerance of the state and support revolutionary actions. They are still a loud minority, but are fastly gaining popularity among the union members with in their rhetoric.
  
  
